1
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:18,738
# I'm mad about the boy

2
00:00:19,925 --> 00:00:25,838
# I know it's stupid to be
mad about the boy

3
00:00:27,557 --> 00:00:32,048
# I'm so ashamed of it,
but must admit

4
00:00:32,186 --> 00:00:39,142
# The sleepless nights
I've had about the boy

5
00:00:42,319 --> 00:00:46,099
# On the silver screen

6
00:00:46,240 --> 00:00:52,272
# He melts my foolish heart
in every single scene

7
00:00:54,414 --> 00:00:57,198
# Although I'm quite aware

8
00:00:57,332 --> 00:01:05,699
# That here and there are traces...
of the cad about the boy

9
00:01:09,218 --> 00:01:14,125
# And Lord knows, I'm not a fool girl

10
00:01:16,100 --> 00:01:20,923
# I really shouldn't care

11
00:01:23,022 --> 00:01:26,803
# Lord knows, I'm not a schoolgirl

12
00:01:26,943 --> 00:01:33,983
# In the flurry of her first affair

13
00:01:35,660 --> 00:01:45,069
# Will it ever cloy, this odd diversity
of misery and joy?

14
00:01:46,961 --> 00:01:51,831
# I'm feeling quite insane
and young again

15
00:01:51,965 --> 00:01:59,253
# And all because I'm mad
about the boy

16
00:02:14,152 --> 00:02:18,525
# I'm feeling quite insane
and young again

17
00:02:18,656 --> 00:02:23,562
# And all because I'm...

18
00:02:24,869 --> 00:02:30,736
#... mad about the boy #

19
00:02:46,515 --> 00:02:50,094
She's the first lady racer.
- But she didn't actually win.

20
00:02:50,226 --> 00:02:54,599
She crossed the line first.
It's so exciting.

21
00:02:54,730 --> 00:02:57,100
Not nearly as exciting
as crossing your mother.

22
00:02:57,232 --> 00:02:59,721
I think we can all ignore that.

23
00:02:59,859 --> 00:03:02,893
Oh, what is that man doing?

24
00:03:07,282 --> 00:03:08,609
Jackson!

25
00:03:08,742 --> 00:03:10,899
Madam?
- What did I tell you?

26
00:03:11,036 --> 00:03:15,244
Put the camellias by the front door
before the guests arrive!

27
00:03:15,374 --> 00:03:16,831
Furber.
- Madam?

28
00:03:16,959 --> 00:03:20,620
Salvage any of Jackson's appalling
pruning and send it to Mrs Holborough

29
00:03:20,753 --> 00:03:25,624
who's kindly offered up a leg of mutton
for dinner, which you'll fetch, Marion.

30
00:03:25,758 --> 00:03:28,756
But Reverend Burton has asked me
to drain the font.

31
00:03:28,886 --> 00:03:32,168
My hands are clearly full.
- I'll go.

32
00:03:32,306 --> 00:03:35,588
Uncle George has posted
the most grizzly clippings

33
00:03:35,724 --> 00:03:37,431
of the Valentine's Day Massacre!

34
00:03:37,560 --> 00:03:38,803
Hilda.

35
00:03:38,937 --> 00:03:43,511
Seven terrified men cut down
in a hail of automatic gun fire!

36
00:03:43,649 --> 00:03:47,892
Made worse by the strays that
came to lap the curdled blood.

37
00:03:48,027 --> 00:03:51,475
Hilda...
- The Devil Dogs! The Hounds of Hell!

38
00:03:51,615 --> 00:03:54,364
The leg of lamb! Now.

39
00:03:58,746 --> 00:04:04,115
Why we try and marry her off to gentry
when plainly she'd prefer an undertaker.

40
00:04:04,251 --> 00:04:08,245
Seating. I'm putting Sarah on your left
and Philip on your right,

41
00:04:08,380 --> 00:04:11,047
so please try and make an effort
to be civil.

42
00:04:11,174 --> 00:04:15,796
Right... I shall go and brush up
on my very small talk.

43
00:04:17,095 --> 00:04:19,335
It might be an awkward meal.

44
00:04:19,472 --> 00:04:23,253
For all we know Sarah's grazing
in greener pastures.

45
00:04:23,392 --> 00:04:28,429
Whilst your brother sows his wild oats
in the South of France with his floozy?

46
00:04:28,565 --> 00:04:33,720
No. We'll keep the home fires burning
until his highness wanders home.

47
00:04:33,860 --> 00:04:35,649
Hmm. Like father did?

48
00:04:35,779 --> 00:04:38,350
Yes. Like your father did.

49
00:04:48,707 --> 00:04:50,912
I've got news, everybody!

50
00:04:51,793 --> 00:04:55,158
You all right, sir?
- No. Are you?

51
00:04:55,296 --> 00:04:58,080
Coping, sir.
- Hear, hear. Well done.

52
00:04:58,216 --> 00:05:01,167
Well done? They look like
they're waiting for a firing squad.

53
00:05:01,301 --> 00:05:05,674
Can't you make them more relaxed?
- Last meal and a cigarette, perhaps?

54
00:05:05,805 --> 00:05:10,012
I can't believe it. You'll never guess.

55
00:05:10,143 --> 00:05:14,007
Houdini escaped the Chinese water
torture only to die of a burst appendix.

56
00:05:14,147 --> 00:05:17,477
How ghastly!
Oh, and Mother's got a telegram.

57
00:05:18,817 --> 00:05:21,022
"Mr and Mrs Whittaker". Your mother.

58
00:05:22,405 --> 00:05:24,479
What's it say, Father?

59
00:05:25,448 --> 00:05:27,735
Perhaps your mother
should read this first.

60
00:05:27,867 --> 00:05:32,608
Oh! That stupid, stupid, stupid boy!

61
00:05:32,746 --> 00:05:35,661
What's happened?
Has there been an accident?

62
00:05:35,791 --> 00:05:38,824
It's John, he's married that f-f-f...
- Francophile?

63
00:05:38,960 --> 00:05:41,365
F-f-f...
- Photographer?

64
00:05:41,504 --> 00:05:44,207
Pharmacist?
- Why are you smirking?

65
00:05:44,341 --> 00:05:47,504
Deploying a smile. One member
of this family may actually be happy.

66
00:05:47,636 --> 00:05:51,332
Don't be absurd! We don't know
anything about this woman. Furber!

67
00:05:51,472 --> 00:05:53,178
Furber!

68
00:05:53,307 --> 00:05:55,878
Oh, not again!
- Madam.

69
00:05:56,018 --> 00:05:58,092
Lord have mercy.

70
00:05:58,228 --> 00:06:01,843
Mister John is coming home with his...
with his wife.

71
00:06:01,981 --> 00:06:04,304
Yes. Their bags have just arrived.
Congratulations, Madam.

72
00:06:04,442 --> 00:06:08,305
I'll be the judge of that. Clear up this
mess and get Cook to send up a ham.

73
00:06:08,446 --> 00:06:12,439
This is from Dover. They'll be half way.
- Yes, Furber. Dress the mutton as ham.

74
00:06:12,575 --> 00:06:14,731
Very sharp,
don't cut yourself.

75
00:06:14,867 --> 00:06:17,403
John married the floozy.
How exciting!

76
00:06:30,799 --> 00:06:35,291
# A room with a view and you

77
00:06:35,427 --> 00:06:38,342
# And no one to worry us

78
00:06:38,472 --> 00:06:44,421
# No one to hurry us through
...this dream we found #

79
00:06:47,104 --> 00:06:50,684
There she blows.
Behold the country cottage.

80
00:06:50,817 --> 00:06:52,891
Oh, Lord, it's enormous.

81
00:06:53,027 --> 00:06:56,973
So, I lied about gingerbread hedges
and obese little children.

82
00:06:57,114 --> 00:07:00,645
How hard to swim is the moat?
- Smoke and mirrors, darling.

83
00:07:00,783 --> 00:07:02,691
Smoke and mirrors.

84
00:07:05,163 --> 00:07:08,944
Oh, by the by, smoking... don't.
Apparently it wilts the azaleas.

85
00:07:09,083 --> 00:07:12,745
That makes no sense. Speak English.
- All will be revealed, darling.

86
00:07:14,838 --> 00:07:19,460
Oh, give me back the wheel of my car.
I'm going back to Detroit!

87
00:07:24,806 --> 00:07:26,713
How romantic!

88
00:07:26,849 --> 00:07:30,013
Here they come! Oh, Furber!

89
00:07:30,144 --> 00:07:32,633
Mister John and his wife
are about to arrive.

90
00:07:32,771 --> 00:07:35,639
I can't see them.
- Your tunnel vision.

91
00:07:38,610 --> 00:07:39,771
Ooh!

92
00:07:44,240 --> 00:07:47,238
Smile, Marion.
- I don't feel like smiling.

93
00:07:47,368 --> 00:07:48,944
You're English, dear. Fake it.

94
00:07:58,710 --> 00:08:02,076
The prodigal son returns
in a blaze of gravel.

95
00:08:02,213 --> 00:08:04,500
Father! You shaved.

96
00:08:07,219 --> 00:08:09,837
Welcome, Madam.

97
00:08:09,971 --> 00:08:12,720
You look gorgeous.

98
00:08:12,849 --> 00:08:14,970
It's so lovely to see you.

99
00:08:19,646 --> 00:08:22,100
Oh, darling. Sorry, sorry!

100
00:08:24,777 --> 00:08:27,265
This is my wife, Larita.

101
00:08:28,362 --> 00:08:31,644
Mrs Whittaker, the pleasure is all mine.

102
00:08:31,783 --> 00:08:33,323
Oh, you're American.

103
00:08:33,450 --> 00:08:36,199
And very welcome. Jim Whittaker.
- This is my father.

104
00:08:36,327 --> 00:08:38,946
I fought alongside many
of your countrymen, Larita,

105
00:08:39,080 --> 00:08:41,747
and I must say it's an honour
to have a comrade in the family.

106
00:08:41,874 --> 00:08:45,038
Thank you.
I do hope I'm not a disappointment.

107
00:08:45,169 --> 00:08:47,622
Far from it.
- And my two little blisters.

108
00:08:47,755 --> 00:08:49,414
Hilda and Marion.

109
00:08:49,548 --> 00:08:52,215
Aren't you the woman
who won the Grand Prix?

110
00:08:52,342 --> 00:08:54,000
First place, before disqualification.

111
00:08:54,135 --> 00:08:58,129
Apparently you need chest hair
to change gears in Monaco.

112
00:08:58,265 --> 00:09:02,175
I saw you in the paper.
I cut your head out. I could just die!

113
00:09:04,019 --> 00:09:07,965
Furber, that suitcase
to the drawing room, and do be careful.

114
00:09:08,106 --> 00:09:11,223
Marion... Golly, you're not a bit
like what we imagined.

115
00:09:11,359 --> 00:09:14,274
Somewhat older, I expect.
Awfully sorry about that.

116
00:09:17,031 --> 00:09:19,317
Before the frostbite sets in...

117
00:09:19,451 --> 00:09:23,740
I'm looking forward to getting acquainted
with the mother of my "Panda".

118
00:09:23,870 --> 00:09:26,904
You'll find me quite uncomplicated,
I'm afraid.

119
00:09:27,040 --> 00:09:29,031
Oh! What are you doing?

120
00:09:29,167 --> 00:09:31,323
Carrying you over the finish line.

121
00:09:35,382 --> 00:09:38,463
Venus de Milo meet my Venus Detroit.

122
00:09:38,592 --> 00:09:40,133
Oh, hello.

123
00:09:40,261 --> 00:09:42,584
Mother's turned our old nursery
into a boudoir.

124
00:09:42,721 --> 00:09:44,795
I wouldn't exactly call
it a boudoir, Hilda.

125
00:09:44,930 --> 00:09:48,094
Marvellous. All those grubby memories
of Little Johnnie.

126
00:09:48,225 --> 00:09:50,299
We had no time
to raid the hothouse.

127
00:09:50,436 --> 00:09:52,675
I only hope we can make you
comfortable.

128
00:09:52,814 --> 00:09:56,014
Don't go to any trouble.
We're only staying a few days.

129
00:09:58,360 --> 00:10:00,517
Aren't we, Johnnie?
- Of course.

130
00:10:00,653 --> 00:10:02,940
And for our next surprise...

131
00:10:06,869 --> 00:10:09,736
What on earth is that?

132
00:10:11,038 --> 00:10:13,574
His master's voice!
A wedding gift from us to you all.

133
00:10:13,707 --> 00:10:17,322
How divine! You should've
got married years ago!

134
00:10:17,460 --> 00:10:24,416
#... another June,
another sunny honeymoon

135
00:10:24,551 --> 00:10:30,665
# Another season, another reason
for making whoopee... #

136
00:10:32,848 --> 00:10:35,171
Come on, little blister. Twirl for me.

137
00:10:41,232 --> 00:10:46,102
Oh, a Continental education.
Not all of us have been so fortunate.

138
00:10:46,237 --> 00:10:49,400
An emotional depiction of the French
postal service, Mrs Whittaker.

139
00:10:49,531 --> 00:10:52,364
Come now, not Mrs Whittaker.
It's "Mother" now.

140
00:10:52,492 --> 00:10:55,359
I don't think we're quite ready
for that yet.

141
00:10:55,495 --> 00:11:01,693
Since time is so clearly against us, why
don't you show Larita up to the nursery?

142
00:11:01,833 --> 00:11:04,322
Dinner's at 8:00.

143
00:11:04,461 --> 00:11:07,495
You didn't tell them?
- One bombshell at a time, darling.

144
00:11:07,630 --> 00:11:12,169
That's not fair! Your poor mother.
How long are we staying?

145
00:11:12,301 --> 00:11:14,208
A few days?

146
00:11:14,344 --> 00:11:19,167
I shoulder the shortcomings of this family
and what do I get in return? A few days!

147
00:11:19,308 --> 00:11:22,010
Look at her. What am I supposed
to do with the bauble of a woman?

148
00:11:22,143 --> 00:11:24,300
Hang her?
- I think she's splendid.

149
00:11:24,438 --> 00:11:28,017
Do you, Hilda? Well, we can all relax.
- She's not what I expected.

150
00:11:28,149 --> 00:11:29,891
She's exactly
what I expected.

151
00:11:30,025 --> 00:11:33,473
Surely not exactly? She wasn't drunk.
- Oh, very funny, Jim.

152
00:11:33,612 --> 00:11:37,227
Reduce this to the burlesque.
- She looks so expensive!

153
00:11:37,366 --> 00:11:39,819
Very.
- Hmm. I like her.

154
00:11:39,950 --> 00:11:42,652
Yes, Jim. We all know what you like.

155
00:11:42,787 --> 00:11:44,161
Mother!

156
00:11:51,002 --> 00:11:53,573
Oh, we have all been sent
to our "wombs".

157
00:11:55,882 --> 00:11:58,999
And so toasty.
- Economics in action.

158
00:11:59,135 --> 00:12:02,086
She keeps half the house closed
to save on heating.

159
00:12:02,221 --> 00:12:04,840
That explains the frosty reception.

160
00:12:04,974 --> 00:12:08,304
Well, darling. Let me warm you up.

161
00:12:30,789 --> 00:12:33,704
Well?
- She's lovely, I'm very proud of you.

162
00:12:33,833 --> 00:12:35,658
Thanks, Father.

163
00:12:35,793 --> 00:12:39,953
John? How long is a few days?

164
00:12:40,088 --> 00:12:43,169
Mother, Larita and I would like
to find a home in London.

165
00:12:43,300 --> 00:12:46,997
But this is your home.
- A home of their own.

166
00:12:49,138 --> 00:12:51,424
But Panda, we need you here.

167
00:12:51,556 --> 00:12:55,929
Since you went off around the Riviera,
we've had to let go of six more people.

168
00:12:56,060 --> 00:12:58,300
If you'd just listened to me
and taken on some machinery.

169
00:12:58,438 --> 00:13:01,851
Wouldn't that be a good idea? I could
run the entire estate single-handedly.

170
00:13:01,983 --> 00:13:05,680
Congratulations on your insight
and your spontaneity.

171
00:13:05,820 --> 00:13:09,102
Sarah and Philip are coming to dinner
tonight, and I have got a table plan

172
00:13:09,240 --> 00:13:11,563
that will take the League
of Nations to unravel.

173
00:13:11,701 --> 00:13:16,654
Tonight? That's absolutely splendid!
- Don't be so fickle in your affections.

174
00:13:16,788 --> 00:13:19,075
Sarah might not be
as accommodating as you expect.

175
00:13:19,207 --> 00:13:21,162
Codswallop. She'll be delighted.

176
00:13:21,292 --> 00:13:25,452
If mother was so desperate for her hand
in marriage, she should've asked herself!

177
00:13:25,588 --> 00:13:27,744
Strange as it may seem,
I agree with your sister.

178
00:13:27,882 --> 00:13:29,623
I think you're wrong.

179
00:13:29,758 --> 00:13:33,170
On certain things, yes. Call her.

180
00:13:33,302 --> 00:13:35,009
Really?
- Really.

181
00:13:35,138 --> 00:13:39,381
Really! If Edgar were here,
he'd do the manly thing.

182
00:13:39,517 --> 00:13:42,006
What? Run away?

183
00:13:46,106 --> 00:13:47,931
Here they come!

184
00:14:02,371 --> 00:14:06,234
And the chequered flag goes to...
Fast work, John!

185
00:14:06,375 --> 00:14:10,534
I should've written, but it happened
so fast, I didn't know where I was.

186
00:14:10,670 --> 00:14:12,874
In Larita's arms, it seems.

187
00:14:13,005 --> 00:14:16,287
Please don't be disappointed.
- Of course I'm disappointed.

188
00:14:16,425 --> 00:14:19,339
But tell me you're happy,
and I'll tell you you're forgiven.

189
00:14:19,469 --> 00:14:23,084
# You're the top,
you're Mahatma Gandhi! #

190
00:14:23,222 --> 00:14:25,793
Panda, don't break out
the brandy just yet.

191
00:14:25,933 --> 00:14:27,675
The hell we're not.

192
00:14:27,811 --> 00:14:31,887
Have I missed something?
- Let sleeping cows stand.

193
00:14:32,022 --> 00:14:33,930
Oh, you plonker!

194
00:14:34,066 --> 00:14:37,147
Rule one, push sleeping cow.

195
00:14:37,277 --> 00:14:39,683
Rule two, get out of the way.

196
00:14:39,820 --> 00:14:42,391
Rule three, remember rule two.

197
00:14:42,532 --> 00:14:45,103
Sarah!
It's so lovely to see you.

198
00:14:45,243 --> 00:14:47,529
I hear your poor father
is not having a good day.

199
00:14:47,662 --> 00:14:50,232
I'm afraid not. He sends his love.

200
00:14:50,372 --> 00:14:53,785
You are a jolly good sport,
turning up like this, that's all I can say.

201
00:14:53,917 --> 00:14:57,164
I wouldn't miss it for the world.
Larita is such a pretty name.

202
00:14:57,295 --> 00:15:00,707
Yes. Excellent for musical comedy.
Hilda!

203
00:15:00,840 --> 00:15:03,956
I hear the cow's in a terrible way.
- I've sent flowers.

204
00:15:04,093 --> 00:15:06,297
And did she eat them?
Touché!

205
00:15:06,428 --> 00:15:08,253
Good evening to you all.

206
00:15:09,097 --> 00:15:11,134
Nobody told me tonight
was fancy dress!

207
00:15:11,265 --> 00:15:14,299
Then why have you come
as the village idiot?

208
00:15:15,853 --> 00:15:18,258
I think I'm snagged.

209
00:15:18,398 --> 00:15:20,637
Let me help you with that.

210
00:15:23,360 --> 00:15:25,102
Holy mother!

211
00:15:26,320 --> 00:15:31,523
Panda? You're forgiven... tenfold.

212
00:15:36,914 --> 00:15:43,029
Sarah Hurst, I'd like to introduce
my wife, Larita Whittaker.

213
00:15:43,170 --> 00:15:46,203
Gosh, I do like the sound of that.

214
00:15:46,339 --> 00:15:48,543
Sarah... finally.

215
00:15:48,674 --> 00:15:52,289
Johnnie talks about you constantly.
- How very annoying for you.

216
00:15:52,427 --> 00:15:57,464
I hope we can be friends.
- We already are. Congratulations.

217
00:15:57,599 --> 00:16:00,597
Er... I'd like to be friends, too.

218
00:16:00,727 --> 00:16:04,389
Larita, my tiresome brother...
- The dishonourable Philip Hurst.

219
00:16:04,522 --> 00:16:06,927
Charmed, my dear lady.
Indeed.

220
00:16:07,066 --> 00:16:09,472
Philip, won't you escort me in?

221
00:16:09,610 --> 00:16:12,857
Of course,
my beautiful, little Sausage Fingers.

222
00:16:12,987 --> 00:16:15,606
That's whet my appetite.
Shall we adjourn to the dining room?

223
00:16:15,740 --> 00:16:17,731
And toast my beautiful bride.

224
00:16:17,866 --> 00:16:20,568
Had we known there was to be
a wedding reception,

225
00:16:20,703 --> 00:16:23,191
we could've lashed out on taffeta!

226
00:16:23,331 --> 00:16:27,159
She's a lot like drowning:
quite pleasant once you stop struggling.

227
00:16:27,292 --> 00:16:31,500
So, John, was Larita's
family able to attend the wedding?

228
00:16:38,343 --> 00:16:39,919
More cabbage, Madam?

229
00:16:40,054 --> 00:16:42,673
There's lots to do, Larita.
You ride, don't you?

230
00:16:42,806 --> 00:16:45,129
Boats, cars or planes?

231
00:16:45,267 --> 00:16:48,715
No, horses, silly.
- Ah, yes, horses.

232
00:16:48,853 --> 00:16:51,555
Faulty steering and unreliable brakes.

233
00:16:52,899 --> 00:16:54,854
I'm stealing that for Stirrup Cup!

234
00:16:54,984 --> 00:16:57,022
Stirrup what?
- Cup.

235
00:16:57,152 --> 00:16:59,901
Every November, Philip and Sarah's
family host the hunt.

236
00:17:00,029 --> 00:17:02,269
Wait until you meet their father,
Lord Hurst, he's terrific.

237
00:17:02,407 --> 00:17:06,235
And Lady Hurst?
- Was terrific, until she... stopped.

238
00:17:08,329 --> 00:17:10,154
Stopped what?
- Living.

239
00:17:11,207 --> 00:17:13,577
Oh, I'm very sorry to hear that.

240
00:17:14,710 --> 00:17:19,414
Between father's polio
and Philip's mania for tipping cows...

241
00:17:19,548 --> 00:17:21,503
Can we please just drop the cows?

242
00:17:21,633 --> 00:17:24,121
I think we'll give the fox a break
this year.

243
00:17:24,260 --> 00:17:28,633
Oh, no hunt? Mrs Winston gave me
her saddle. I've had a wax.

244
00:17:30,391 --> 00:17:33,638
Your father and I conspired to make
John the Master of the Hunt.

245
00:17:33,768 --> 00:17:37,015
People come from far and wide.
It's such a shame to disappoint them.

246
00:17:37,147 --> 00:17:38,889
Very thoughtful, Mother.

247
00:17:39,023 --> 00:17:41,725
You do hunt,
I take it, Larita?

248
00:17:41,860 --> 00:17:44,941
Hypocrites, gossips
or defenceless animals?

249
00:17:45,070 --> 00:17:46,349
Bravo!

250
00:17:46,488 --> 00:17:48,525
You wouldn't get her to the start.

251
00:17:48,657 --> 00:17:52,272
We have another
conscientious objector, Father.

252
00:17:52,410 --> 00:17:56,653
Company! Do you object to the circus
or the slaughter, Major?

253
00:17:56,790 --> 00:17:59,195
I support Sheppard's position
on pacifism.

254
00:17:59,333 --> 00:18:03,197
Good for you.
So, when does the carnage begin?

255
00:18:03,337 --> 00:18:06,999
After the War Widow's Revue,
but before the craft fair,

256
00:18:07,132 --> 00:18:09,004
in between the Dog Show and the shoot.

257
00:18:09,133 --> 00:18:13,458
Don't forget the highlight. Mother's
Christmas dance is the hot ticket.

258
00:18:13,597 --> 00:18:16,760
She's ordered the most exquisite
Japanese lanterns.

259
00:18:16,890 --> 00:18:19,461
From Japan?
- No, Fortnum & Mason's.

260
00:18:19,602 --> 00:18:23,263
Oh, yes.
Prepare for a whirlwind, Larita.

261
00:18:24,647 --> 00:18:26,354
I'm breathless already.

262
00:18:30,278 --> 00:18:33,441
I won't make it to Christmas.
You won't need to.

263
00:18:33,572 --> 00:18:36,108
I won't make it to breakfast!
What were we just eating?

264
00:18:36,241 --> 00:18:38,812
The lumpy grey and beige concoction?

265
00:18:38,952 --> 00:18:43,076
Oh, yes. That's the word
I was looking for..."greige".

266
00:18:43,205 --> 00:18:46,618
Absolutely no idea.
But it is the speciality of the house.

267
00:18:46,751 --> 00:18:50,034
Incoming! Have you met my namesake?
He's very good in bed.

268
00:18:50,171 --> 00:18:52,838
Shh! They'll hear you.
- I don't care.

269
00:18:52,965 --> 00:18:54,588
I do.

270
00:18:55,842 --> 00:18:58,591
I know we need the heat,
but please don't smoke.

271
00:18:58,720 --> 00:19:01,090
Mother's clairvoyant about these things.

272
00:19:01,223 --> 00:19:03,676
She loathes me, Johnnie.

273
00:19:03,807 --> 00:19:07,338
I'm a gold-digger, burrowing in
from the land of opportunists.

274
00:19:08,812 --> 00:19:11,301
Your father's an interesting study,
though.

275
00:19:11,439 --> 00:19:13,513
Quietly sardonic. I like that in a man.

276
00:19:13,650 --> 00:19:16,932
That won't earn you many
brownie points under this roof.

277
00:19:18,570 --> 00:19:22,150
After the Armistice,
Father didn't come straight home.

278
00:19:22,282 --> 00:19:25,694
He caroused around France and Italy,
drinking, having affairs...

279
00:19:25,828 --> 00:19:29,276
A lot of men did similar...
couldn't settle down.

280
00:19:29,414 --> 00:19:32,780
Why didn't she go after him?
- A question of pride.

281
00:19:32,917 --> 00:19:35,038
He finally just wandered home.

282
00:19:35,169 --> 00:19:38,369
Still a bit of a sore point.
We try not to speak about it.

283
00:19:38,506 --> 00:19:39,915
Except in public.

284
00:19:40,048 --> 00:19:42,963
You see, she feels
she's missed out on something.

285
00:19:43,093 --> 00:19:45,664
Which means, of course,
she's missed out on everything.

286
00:19:45,803 --> 00:19:49,251
Exactly. The war robbed her
of all her expectations.

287
00:19:49,391 --> 00:19:52,093
She takes one look
at a woman like you...

288
00:19:52,226 --> 00:19:55,473
The harlot stealing into the nursery...

289
00:19:55,604 --> 00:19:57,760
The delicious concubine...

290
00:19:57,898 --> 00:19:59,889
...with the delectable ears...

291
00:20:00,692 --> 00:20:02,184
...nose...

292
00:20:02,735 --> 00:20:04,193
...neck.

293
00:20:06,030 --> 00:20:07,523
I could just...

294
00:20:08,907 --> 00:20:10,364
...eat you.

295
00:20:10,492 --> 00:20:12,898
After that meal I'm not surprised.

296
00:20:21,210 --> 00:20:26,081
# '... I'm mad about the boy! ' #

297
00:21:07,210 --> 00:21:11,868
Dear Lord, thank you for bringing
John and his floozy home safely.

298
00:21:20,555 --> 00:21:23,672
'Hmm... John! '

299
00:21:32,608 --> 00:21:36,305
Why is Larita always so late?
- You can't hurry perfection.

300
00:21:36,445 --> 00:21:40,818
Edgar was never late for a meal.
- He's missed a few lately.

301
00:21:40,948 --> 00:21:44,527
Good morning.
How are we all on this glorious day?

302
00:21:44,661 --> 00:21:48,358
There she is! Morning, darling.

303
00:21:51,333 --> 00:21:53,538
What would Madam like for breakfast?

304
00:21:54,294 --> 00:21:57,327
I think Madam will get more sustenance
from a kipper.

305
00:21:57,464 --> 00:22:00,710
But it won't be as much fun.
- Aren't you riding with us?

306
00:22:00,842 --> 00:22:03,165
Darling, I think it's about high time

307
00:22:03,302 --> 00:22:07,248
that your mother and I have
an intimate tête-à-tête.

308
00:22:07,388 --> 00:22:10,836
Just us girls.
- Lovely.

309
00:22:10,976 --> 00:22:13,381
What a frightening thought.

310
00:22:15,772 --> 00:22:22,977
Two hemispheres under one roof.
Papua New Guinea, India, the Argentine.

311
00:22:26,532 --> 00:22:29,446
I may not have travelled,
but the world has come to me.

312
00:22:29,576 --> 00:22:32,823
Are you coming down with something?

313
00:22:32,954 --> 00:22:36,154
Pollen.
But if I hold my breath long enough...

314
00:22:36,290 --> 00:22:38,032
How peculiar.

315
00:22:38,167 --> 00:22:40,453
Which is why we should
get to know one another.

316
00:22:40,585 --> 00:22:43,499
Where does one start?
- Shall I make headway?

317
00:22:43,629 --> 00:22:47,209
I was born in Detroit.
My father worked in the steel plant.

318
00:22:47,341 --> 00:22:50,008
He was one of the first
lured over to Henry Ford.

319
00:22:50,136 --> 00:22:52,126
Ah, hence the love of motoring?

320
00:22:52,263 --> 00:22:54,716
Yes, but I also love animals.

321
00:22:54,848 --> 00:22:57,004
I am a city girl.
I take chickens to the vet.

322
00:22:57,142 --> 00:22:58,765
Oh!

323
00:22:58,894 --> 00:23:03,018
You can't be squeamish about livestock
now that you are living in the country.

324
00:23:03,148 --> 00:23:05,222
Which was never my intention.

325
00:23:05,357 --> 00:23:08,225
I was happily carving out a niche
for myself on the race circuit

326
00:23:08,360 --> 00:23:12,650
when I was unexpectedly flagged down
by someone irresistible.

327
00:23:14,450 --> 00:23:18,313
Remarrying was the farthest thing
from my mind.

328
00:23:20,330 --> 00:23:22,036
I see...

329
00:23:24,583 --> 00:23:26,325
May I ask?

330
00:23:27,252 --> 00:23:30,831
Oh, dead, unfortunately. No children.

331
00:23:30,964 --> 00:23:34,958
Oh...
How disappointing for you.

332
00:23:35,093 --> 00:23:37,463
Still, he provided well, though?

333
00:23:37,595 --> 00:23:42,383
Yes, but there were a lot of hidden costs
associated with his passing.

334
00:23:42,516 --> 00:23:47,506
Oh, that beautiful motor car... Surely,
you must have independent means?

335
00:23:47,646 --> 00:23:50,348
I'm more than happy
to discuss my means,

336
00:23:50,481 --> 00:23:52,768
but I think you'll be a tad disappointed.

337
00:23:52,901 --> 00:23:55,271
The car is my sole source of income.

338
00:23:55,403 --> 00:23:58,567
Which makes living in London
an imperative.

339
00:23:58,697 --> 00:24:01,185
But what will John do in the city?

340
00:24:01,325 --> 00:24:03,695
Work. It's not uncommon.

341
00:24:03,827 --> 00:24:05,485
Oh!

342
00:24:06,580 --> 00:24:09,661
John was brought up in the country,
Larita.

343
00:24:09,790 --> 00:24:11,911
Where will he work?

344
00:24:12,042 --> 00:24:15,953
Chalk Farm, perhaps?
Or St-Martin-In-The-Fields?

345
00:24:16,088 --> 00:24:20,545
I know this is not perfect so that's
why I'm asking for your guidance.

346
00:24:20,675 --> 00:24:23,957
So, please, how can I make this
pleasant for everybody?

347
00:24:24,095 --> 00:24:28,918
Well, erm... wartime experience dictates
that you keep your head down

348
00:24:29,058 --> 00:24:31,013
and you fit in as well as you can.

349
00:24:31,143 --> 00:24:35,884
Oh, there's a war on?
- Oh, no... not necessarily.

350
00:24:36,815 --> 00:24:39,979
Australian mimosa. Mmm... beautiful.

351
00:24:41,277 --> 00:24:43,564
Oh...

352
00:24:48,575 --> 00:24:52,783
And then the British troops opened fire...
How grizzly!

353
00:24:52,913 --> 00:24:56,408
How'd it go, Mother?
- Oh, marvellous!

354
00:24:56,541 --> 00:24:57,784
Marvellous.

355
00:25:03,881 --> 00:25:05,955
Thanks for the invitation!

356
00:25:14,014 --> 00:25:15,970
Thanks for the invitation!

357
00:25:16,100 --> 00:25:18,635
Oh, it's Lord Hurst!

358
00:25:18,768 --> 00:25:21,683
I fear storm clouds are gathering,
Mrs Whit.

359
00:25:21,813 --> 00:25:23,934
Stop being maudlin, Father.

360
00:25:24,065 --> 00:25:26,221
It's the future!
- Spanner!

361
00:25:26,359 --> 00:25:30,815
Father, allow me to introduce
Panda's new chauffeuse.

362
00:25:30,947 --> 00:25:34,609
Lovely La-La-Larita.
- Watch it, Philip.

363
00:25:34,741 --> 00:25:38,107
My son is prone to fabrication,
but I can see on this occasion

364
00:25:38,244 --> 00:25:40,946
he has been perfectly frank,
Mrs Whittaker.

365
00:25:42,082 --> 00:25:46,075
Yes, that's right.
There are two of us now.

366
00:25:46,210 --> 00:25:48,912
No shortage of wits
around here any more.

367
00:25:49,046 --> 00:25:52,577
OK, stand back! I give you, the future!

368
00:25:57,096 --> 00:26:00,047
All right, John.
You can take my baby out for a spin.

369
00:26:01,766 --> 00:26:05,178
Ha-ha! Allergies.
She inflates like a puffer fish.

370
00:26:05,311 --> 00:26:07,847
You just want to squeeze her
until she pops.

371
00:26:07,980 --> 00:26:10,764
#... working at the car wash

372
00:26:15,278 --> 00:26:17,683
# You might not ever strike it rich

373
00:26:19,324 --> 00:26:22,405
# But let me tell you,
it's better than digging a ditch

374
00:26:22,535 --> 00:26:25,948
# Working at the car wash!

375
00:26:26,080 --> 00:26:28,782
# Working at the car wash, man

376
00:26:28,915 --> 00:26:31,664
# Come on, now, sing it to me

377
00:26:32,711 --> 00:26:35,330
# It's better than digging a ditch... #

378
00:26:47,306 --> 00:26:50,139
The missus is a bit trigger-happy
this week.

379
00:26:50,268 --> 00:26:52,223
Bleeding tinnitus is killing me.

380
00:26:52,353 --> 00:26:56,643
I like the new Mrs Whit. Reminds me
of the old one before the war.

381
00:26:56,774 --> 00:26:59,974
Only more reasonable. You can tell
she's run her own household.

382
00:27:00,109 --> 00:27:01,816
Oh, be silent!

383
00:27:01,945 --> 00:27:05,725
Good morning,
Furber, Jackson, Millie, and?

384
00:27:05,865 --> 00:27:08,650
Cook, I can't call you a verb.
Your name?

385
00:27:09,494 --> 00:27:10,951
Beatrice.

386
00:27:14,498 --> 00:27:18,538
All right, all right... it's Doris.
Sorry, Madam.

387
00:27:18,668 --> 00:27:21,204
Always wanted to be called Beatrice.

388
00:27:21,337 --> 00:27:25,994
Well, Beatrice, would you mind
if I helped myself in the mornings?

389
00:27:26,134 --> 00:27:29,251
I fear I shall be rising later and later.

390
00:27:29,387 --> 00:27:31,875
Well... if it pleases, Mrs Whit.

391
00:27:34,099 --> 00:27:35,971
The point of the bell?

392
00:27:36,100 --> 00:27:39,300
When I ring it, you come to me,
not the other way round!

393
00:27:40,438 --> 00:27:42,559
Larita. May I have a word?

394
00:27:43,774 --> 00:27:45,480
Come along!

395
00:27:48,403 --> 00:27:51,318
Would you please refrain
from chatting to the staff?

396
00:27:51,447 --> 00:27:54,196
It's chore enough trying to keep
this motley crew together.

397
00:27:54,325 --> 00:27:58,401
I had a brilliant French maid in Paris.
Perhaps I should send for her?

398
00:27:58,537 --> 00:28:00,943
Thank you, no... erm...

399
00:28:01,081 --> 00:28:05,454
I'd prefer to keep English
the first language in this household.

400
00:28:05,585 --> 00:28:07,208
Ah, there you are.

401
00:28:07,337 --> 00:28:09,826
I say! Anyone for tennis?

402
00:28:09,964 --> 00:28:11,291
Yes. You!

403
00:28:11,424 --> 00:28:13,829
John, Shackleton wouldn't let
a dog out today!

404
00:28:13,967 --> 00:28:16,041
The fog has lifted
and Whittakers don't do winter.

405
00:28:16,178 --> 00:28:19,425
You go ahead, darling.
I'll play with myself.

406
00:28:19,557 --> 00:28:22,674
No, really. I'm a lot of fun.
- Ooh...

407
00:28:22,810 --> 00:28:25,512
John!
It's brass monkeys out here!

408
00:28:29,357 --> 00:28:32,936
Day one of the Antarctic Open.
Mister Whittaker to serve.

409
00:28:36,280 --> 00:28:38,484
Hole in one!
- Deuce.

410
00:28:38,615 --> 00:28:42,561
I see your pair of deuces
and I raise you a tenner.

411
00:28:42,702 --> 00:28:45,653
The Titanic could have hit that!

412
00:28:45,789 --> 00:28:49,699
Sarah, you're an embarrassment to
the family name. I'll have you killed.

413
00:28:49,833 --> 00:28:53,530
Good God! What's wrong with you?
No! Stop now!

414
00:28:53,670 --> 00:28:56,870
Stop, everybody! Listen!
- Shoot the court jester!

415
00:28:57,007 --> 00:29:00,953
Nice backhand!
- Is that a backhand compliment?

416
00:29:01,094 --> 00:29:04,294
# Mad dogs and Englishmen
go out in the midday sun!

417
00:29:04,430 --> 00:29:07,926
# The Japanese don't care to,
the Chinese wouldn't dare to

418
00:29:08,058 --> 00:29:10,973
# Hindus and Argentines sleep firmly
from twelve to one

419
00:29:11,103 --> 00:29:14,433
# But Englishmen detest a siesta... #

420
00:29:14,563 --> 00:29:18,059
Laurel and Hardy step up
to the crease. The fillies are lining up.

421
00:29:18,192 --> 00:29:21,973
Miss Hilda Whittaker looking most
fetching in her feed bag and bridle!

422
00:29:28,785 --> 00:29:30,941
One woman's heaven...

423
00:29:32,330 --> 00:29:34,202
Oh, she's absolutely beautiful.

424
00:29:36,542 --> 00:29:40,204
Broken, tarnished
and completely useless.

425
00:29:41,504 --> 00:29:45,545
Things guaranteed
to keep my wife at bay.

426
00:29:45,675 --> 00:29:47,381
May I?

427
00:29:47,510 --> 00:29:49,915
If you don't mind
getting your hands dirty.

428
00:29:50,054 --> 00:29:53,882
In Detroit, what we lack in dirt,
we make up for in filth.

429
00:29:54,016 --> 00:29:57,132
Your first husband
from that neck of the woods?

430
00:29:57,269 --> 00:29:59,757
Oh... well, word gets about.

431
00:30:02,066 --> 00:30:04,850
So where is he now?
- Dead.

432
00:30:07,028 --> 00:30:08,900
Cancer.

433
00:30:09,030 --> 00:30:11,353
He was a fair bit older than me.

434
00:30:11,490 --> 00:30:15,235
I spent a while playing the unmerry
widow but the black wore thin.

435
00:30:16,118 --> 00:30:19,815
You didn't care for him, I gather?
- I cared too much.

436
00:30:19,956 --> 00:30:23,784
Life was just such an unpleasant
experience for the man, I...

437
00:30:24,377 --> 00:30:27,659
I'd be a liar to say I wasn't glad
when he was relieved of it.

438
00:30:36,263 --> 00:30:39,629
When were you last in France?
- Just after the war?

439
00:30:39,766 --> 00:30:41,721
On a personal reconnaissance,

440
00:30:41,850 --> 00:30:46,673
trying to ascertain what exactly
all those fine young men had died for.

441
00:30:48,315 --> 00:30:51,064
Apparently, I'm of the romantic
Lost Generation.

442
00:30:52,359 --> 00:30:54,101
What did you lose?

443
00:30:55,113 --> 00:30:57,187
I'm not sure.

444
00:31:55,375 --> 00:31:57,828
Oh, hello... hello.

445
00:31:57,960 --> 00:32:01,789
Who was the tiny tank?
Who's a pretty, little, cheeky chorizo?

446
00:32:03,091 --> 00:32:06,538
On bended knees,
please come and play with me.

447
00:32:06,676 --> 00:32:08,880
Johnnie dear,
you know how much I love you,

448
00:32:09,012 --> 00:32:12,709
so please try to take this
in the best possible light.

449
00:32:12,850 --> 00:32:16,926
I'm getting a machine gun
and mowing down your entire family.

450
00:32:17,061 --> 00:32:20,676
That's fairly disappointing. I thought
you and Father were getting along.

451
00:32:20,815 --> 00:32:23,434
Yes, I might spare the men folk.

452
00:32:23,567 --> 00:32:27,264
But it's awfully dispiriting.
We have absolutely no privacy here.

453
00:32:27,404 --> 00:32:29,892
I never needed any privacy before.
This is my home.

454
00:32:30,032 --> 00:32:32,734
It's not mine.
And I very much want one.

455
00:32:34,160 --> 00:32:39,232
# We're all alone,
no chaperone can get our number

456
00:32:39,372 --> 00:32:43,496
# The world's aslumber,
let's misbehave

457
00:32:46,713 --> 00:32:49,415
Timing is everything, you little brute!

458
00:32:49,548 --> 00:32:52,830
Umpire at least.
Philip is pining for you.

459
00:32:52,969 --> 00:32:56,879
If I knew you played tennis, I never
would've signed the marriage certificate!

460
00:32:57,014 --> 00:32:58,755
Ow!

461
00:33:12,069 --> 00:33:14,604
Not a bad day for it.

462
00:33:14,738 --> 00:33:16,528
Reading.

463
00:33:16,656 --> 00:33:19,524
My fiancé, Edgar,
was always hiding behind books.

464
00:33:19,659 --> 00:33:24,151
Erm... you're needed on the tennis court.
John was just asking after you.

465
00:33:24,288 --> 00:33:27,488
Would you like to see
a photo of him... my Edgar?

466
00:33:27,624 --> 00:33:28,868
Poppy!

467
00:33:32,129 --> 00:33:35,292
That's Enrico Caruso.
- Who's dead, I know that...

468
00:33:35,423 --> 00:33:38,871
But if you ignore
the nose and the mouth...

469
00:33:39,010 --> 00:33:42,422
...and the ears...
there's a striking resemblance.

470
00:33:44,348 --> 00:33:46,469
I don't actually have a picture of Edgar.

471
00:33:47,893 --> 00:33:49,930
Well... mustn't keep you.

472
00:33:50,062 --> 00:33:54,102
No, no. Of course. Looking forward
to getting stuck in to a good book.

473
00:33:54,231 --> 00:33:56,269
